\title{Pubmed Database}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Direct REST API access to PubMed. Advanced Boolean/MeSH queries, E-utilities API, batch processing, citation management. For Python workflows, prefer biopython (Bio.Entrez). Use this for direct HTTP/REST work or custom API implementations."}

\subtree{
\title{PubMed Database}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{PubMed is the U.S. National Library of Medicine's comprehensive database providing free access to MEDLINE and life sciences literature. Construct advanced queries with Boolean operators, MeSH terms, and field tags, access data programmatically via E-utilities API for systematic reviews and literature analysis.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{Searching for biomedical or life sciences research articles}
\li{Constructing complex search queries with Boolean operators, field tags, or MeSH terms}
\li{Conducting systematic literature reviews or meta-analyses}
\li{Accessing PubMed data programmatically via the E-utilities API}
\li{Finding articles by specific criteria (author, journal, publication date, article type)}
\li{Retrieving citation information, abstracts, or full-text articles}
\li{Working with PMIDs (PubMed IDs) or DOIs}
\li{Creating automated workflows for literature monitoring or data extraction}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. Advanced Search Query Construction}
\p{Construct sophisticated PubMed queries using Boolean operators, field tags, and specialized syntax.}

\p{\strong{Basic Search Strategies}:}

\ul{
\li{Combine concepts with Boolean operators (AND, OR, NOT)}
\li{Use field tags to limit searches to specific record parts}
\li{Employ phrase searching with double quotes for exact matches}
\li{Apply wildcards for term variations}
\li{Use proximity searching for terms within specified distances}
}

\p{\strong{Example Queries}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Recent systematic reviews on diabetes treatment
diabetes mellitus[mh] AND treatment[tiab] AND systematic review[pt] AND 2023:2024[dp]

# Clinical trials comparing two drugs
(metformin[nm] OR insulin[nm]) AND diabetes mellitus, type 2[mh] AND randomized controlled trial[pt]

# Author-specific research
smith ja[au] AND cancer[tiab] AND 2023[dp] AND english[la]
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{When to consult search_syntax.md}:}

\ul{
\li{Need comprehensive list of available field tags}
\li{Require detailed explanation of search operators}
\li{Constructing complex proximity searches}
\li{Understanding automatic term mapping behavior}
\li{Need specific syntax for date ranges, wildcards, or special characters}
}

\pre{\startverb
Grep pattern for field tags: `\[au\]|\[ti\]|\[ab\]|\[mh\]|\[pt\]|\[dp\]`
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. MeSH Terms and Controlled Vocabulary}
\p{Use Medical Subject Headings (MeSH) for precise, consistent searching across the biomedical literature.}

\p{\strong{MeSH Searching}:}

\ul{
\li{[mh] tag searches MeSH terms with automatic inclusion of narrower terms}
\li{[majr] tag limits to articles where the topic is the main focus}
\li{Combine MeSH terms with subheadings for specificity (e.g., diabetes mellitus/therapy[mh])}
}

\p{\strong{Common MeSH Subheadings}:}

\ul{
\li{/diagnosis - Diagnostic methods}
\li{/drug therapy - Pharmaceutical treatment}
\li{/epidemiology - Disease patterns and prevalence}
\li{/etiology - Disease causes}
\li{/prevention & control - Preventive measures}
\li{/therapy - Treatment approaches}
}

\p{\strong{Example}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Diabetes therapy with specific focus
diabetes mellitus, type 2[mh]/drug therapy AND cardiovascular diseases[mh]/prevention & control
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Article Type and Publication Filtering}
\p{Filter results by publication type, date, text availability, and other attributes.}

\p{\strong{Publication Types} (use [pt] field tag):}

\ul{
\li{Clinical Trial}
\li{Meta-Analysis}
\li{Randomized Controlled Trial}
\li{Review}
\li{Systematic Review}
\li{Case Reports}
\li{Guideline}
}

\p{\strong{Date Filtering}:}

\ul{
\li{Single year: \code{\startverb 2024[dp]\stopverb}}
\li{Date range: \code{\startverb 2020:2024[dp]\stopverb}}
\li{Specific date: \code{\startverb 2024/03/15[dp]\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Text Availability}:}

\ul{
\li{Free full text: Add \code{\startverb AND free full text[sb]\stopverb} to query}
\li{Has abstract: Add \code{\startverb AND hasabstract[text]\stopverb} to query}
}

\p{\strong{Example}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Recent free full-text RCTs on hypertension
hypertension[mh] AND randomized controlled trial[pt] AND 2023:2024[dp] AND free full text[sb]
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Programmatic Access via E-utilities API}
\p{Access PubMed data programmatically using the NCBI E-utilities REST API for automation and bulk operations.}

\p{\strong{Core API Endpoints}:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{ESearch} - Search database and retrieve PMIDs}
\li{\strong{EFetch} - Download full records in various formats}
\li{\strong{ESummary} - Get document summaries}
\li{\strong{EPost} - Upload UIDs for batch processing}
\li{\strong{ELink} - Find related articles and linked data}
}

\p{\strong{Basic Workflow}:}

\pre{\startverb
import requests

# Step 1: Search for articles
base_url = "https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/"
search_url = f"{base_url}esearch.fcgi"
params = {
    "db": "pubmed",
    "term": "diabetes[tiab] AND 2024[dp]",
    "retmax": 100,
    "retmode": "json",
    "api_key": "YOUR_API_KEY"  # Optional but recommended
}
response = requests.get(search_url, params=params)
pmids = response.json()["esearchresult"]["idlist"]

# Step 2: Fetch article details
fetch_url = f"{base_url}efetch.fcgi"
params = {
    "db": "pubmed",
    "id": ",".join(pmids),
    "rettype": "abstract",
    "retmode": "text",
    "api_key": "YOUR_API_KEY"
}
response = requests.get(fetch_url, params=params)
abstracts = response.text
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rate Limits}:}

\ul{
\li{Without API key: 3 requests/second}
\li{With API key: 10 requests/second}
\li{Always include User-Agent header}
}

\p{\strong{Best Practices}:}

\ul{
\li{Use history server (usehistory=y) for large result sets}
\li{Implement batch operations via EPost for multiple UIDs}
\li{Cache results locally to minimize redundant calls}
\li{Respect rate limits to avoid service disruption}
}

\p{\strong{When to consult api_reference.md}:}

\ul{
\li{Need detailed endpoint documentation}
\li{Require parameter specifications for each E-utility}
\li{Constructing batch operations or history server workflows}
\li{Understanding response formats (XML, JSON, text)}
\li{Troubleshooting API errors or rate limit issues}
}

\p{Grep pattern for API endpoints: \code{\startverb esearch|efetch|esummary|epost|elink|einfo\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Citation Matching and Article Retrieval}
\p{Find articles using partial citation information or specific identifiers.}

\p{\strong{By Identifier}:}

\pre{\startverb
# By PMID
12345678[pmid]

# By DOI
10.1056/NEJMoa123456[doi]

# By PMC ID
PMC123456[pmc]
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Citation Matching} (via ECitMatch API): Use journal name, year, volume, page, and author to find PMIDs:}

\pre{\startverb
Format: journal|year|volume|page|author|key|
Example: Science|2008|320|5880|1185|key1|
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{By Author and Metadata}:}

\pre{\startverb
# First author with year and topic
smith ja[1au] AND 2023[dp] AND cancer[tiab]

# Journal, volume, and page
nature[ta] AND 2024[dp] AND 456[vi] AND 123-130[pg]
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Systematic Literature Reviews}
\p{Conduct comprehensive literature searches for systematic reviews and meta-analyses.}

\p{\strong{PICO Framework} (Population, Intervention, Comparison, Outcome): Structure clinical research questions systematically:}

\pre{\startverb
# Example: Diabetes treatment effectiveness
# P: diabetes mellitus, type 2[mh]
# I: metformin[nm]
# C: lifestyle modification[tiab]
# O: glycemic control[tiab]

diabetes mellitus, type 2[mh] AND
(metformin[nm] OR lifestyle modification[tiab]) AND
glycemic control[tiab] AND
randomized controlled trial[pt]
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Comprehensive Search Strategy}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Include multiple synonyms and MeSH terms
(disease name[tiab] OR disease name[mh] OR synonym[tiab]) AND
(treatment[tiab] OR therapy[tiab] OR intervention[tiab]) AND
(systematic review[pt] OR meta-analysis[pt] OR randomized controlled trial[pt]) AND
2020:2024[dp] AND
english[la]
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Search Refinement}:}

\ol{
\li{Start broad, review results}
\li{Add specificity with field tags}
\li{Apply date and publication type filters}
\li{Use Advanced Search to view query translation}
\li{Combine search history for complex queries}
}

\p{\strong{When to consult common_queries.md}:}

\ul{
\li{Need example queries for specific disease types or research areas}
\li{Require templates for different study designs}
\li{Looking for population-specific query patterns (pediatric, geriatric, etc.)}
\li{Constructing methodology-specific searches}
\li{Need quality filters or best practice patterns}
}

\p{Grep pattern for query examples: \code{\startverb diabetes|cancer|cardiovascular|clinical trial|systematic review\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{7. Search History and Saved Searches}
\p{Use PubMed's search history and My NCBI features for efficient research workflows.}

\p{\strong{Search History} (via Advanced Search):}

\ul{
\li{Maintains up to 100 searches}
\li{Expires after 8 hours of inactivity}
\li{Combine previous searches using # references}
\li{Preview result counts before executing}
}

\p{\strong{Example}:}

\pre{\startverb
#1: diabetes mellitus[mh]
#2: cardiovascular diseases[mh]
#3: #1 AND #2 AND risk factors[tiab]
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{My NCBI Features}:}

\ul{
\li{Save searches indefinitely}
\li{Set up email alerts for new matching articles}
\li{Create collections of saved articles}
\li{Organize research by project or topic}
}

\p{\strong{RSS Feeds}: Create RSS feeds for any search to monitor new publications in your area of interest.}
}

\subtree{
\title{8. Related Articles and Citation Discovery}
\p{Find related research and explore citation networks.}

\p{\strong{Similar Articles Feature}: Every PubMed article includes pre-calculated related articles based on:}

\ul{
\li{Title and abstract similarity}
\li{MeSH term overlap}
\li{Weighted algorithmic matching}
}

\p{\strong{ELink for Related Data}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Find related articles programmatically
elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&db=pubmed&id=PMID&cmd=neighbor
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Citation Links}:}

\ul{
\li{LinkOut to full text from publishers}
\li{Links to PubMed Central free articles}
\li{Connections to related NCBI databases (GenBank, ClinicalTrials.gov, etc.)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{9. Export and Citation Management}
\p{Export search results in various formats for citation management and further analysis.}

\p{\strong{Export Formats}:}

\ul{
\li{.nbib files for reference managers (Zotero, Mendeley, EndNote)}
\li{AMA, MLA, APA, NLM citation styles}
\li{CSV for data analysis}
\li{XML for programmatic processing}
}

\p{\strong{Clipboard and Collections}:}

\ul{
\li{Clipboard: Temporary storage for up to 500 items (8-hour expiration)}
\li{Collections: Permanent storage via My NCBI account}
}

\p{\strong{Batch Export via API}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Export citations in MEDLINE format
efetch.fcgi?db=pubmed&id=PMID1,PMID2&rettype=medline&retmode=text
\stopverb}
}
}

